These frogs produce white, sticky secretions from their dorsal glands that undoubtedly serve an anti-predator function. One of the subadult males (SV = 
53.3 mm
) exhibited a defensive display in which the body was inflated with air while either being held to the ground (
Fig. 6A
), with the rear of the body elevated off the ground (
Fig. 6B
), or with the entire body held off the ground (
Fig. 6C
). The entire display serves to clearly exhibit the bright-orange blotches in the groin and on the rear of the legs (
Fig. 6D
), which presumably serve as a signal to warn of the thick glandular secretions that are readily exuded from the dorsum.
